message: Hey future crafter! Here's what I learned: Always cook raw ingredients first with the 'stove' (e.g., raw beef/fish/egg -> cooked). A good recipe for 80 points is 'Cooked Protein + Cooked Vegetable + Grain'. Don't add more than 3 distinct ingredient types to a combined item, as a fourth item (especially a second vegetable or another grain) almost always makes it 'overcomplicated' and drops the value significantly, often to negative. The 'water' tool tends to reduce value or introduce 'soaked' features, so use it with extreme caution. Cooking 'fish' is fine, but combining it too much follows the same 'overcomplicated' rule as other ingredients. Aim for 80 and submit, trying for 100 is risky!

The 'water' tool didn't seem to add value in my experience.

message: To succeed, start by combining two vegetables, then add a grain to create a 'raw mix'. Immediately cook this mix with the 游댠 stove. This typically yields a good value (e.g., 60). If you have a protein (like bacon or egg), cook it separately with the 游댠 stove, then combine the cooked protein with your cooked vegetable-grain mix for a potentially higher value (up to 80). message: Cooking raw proteins and vegetables with the stove generally increases their value. Combining a cooked protein with a grain, then adding a single vegetable (cooked or raw), typically creates a high-value item (around 60-80). However, be cautious: combining two already complex items or adding a fourth component often leads to 'overcomplicated' items with negative values. Once you have a 3-component item with a good value, it's often safest to submit. The 'DONT USE FISH' hint was a red herring; cooked fish works fine.
